[1] Indonesia
Date: 10 Apr 2007
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Actualidad [trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://actualidad.terra.es/sociedad/articulo/mueren_yakarta_dengue_principios_ano_1504008.htm>

In Jakarta, 42 people have died of dengue since the 1st of the year
[2007], and thousands of neighbors in the capital of Indonesia have
been infected during this period, according to the Health Service.
The Jakarta government considers this dengue outbreak to be "an
extraordinary situation," according to the Subdirector of Regional
Health Services, Salimar Salim.
Just in the month of March [2007], 4423 cases have been registered in
Jakarta, compared to 2249 registered during the same period in the
previous year [2006], he added.
Jakarta has not lived through a similar dengue outbreak for 3 years,
when the disease caused 90 deaths in the city, with 20 640
[individuals] infected.
It is hoped that the number of [dengue] infections will decline this
month [April 2007] with the end of the rainy season, which, in
Indonesia, occurs between October and March. Dengue is transmitted by
the mosquito _Aedes aegypti_, which is more abundant during this
season, especially in areas where water accumulates.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[ProMED requests again any information available about action taken
for vector mosquito control or about the dengue virus type or types
that are circulating during this outbreak. ProMED thanks Brent
Barrett and A-Lan Banks for sending in similar reports. An article in
the 11 Apr 2007 Jakarta Post, which, unfortunately, is only available
to subscribers, reports that the Jakarta government is considering
legal enforcement to compel citizens to eliminate _Aedes aegypti_
breeding sites in homes. Without an aggressive public education
effort, willing compliance will be difficult to achieve. A map of
Indonesia can be accessed at:
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/indonesia_pol_2002.jpg>.
- Mod.TY]
