[4] Dominican Republic
Date: 10 Apr 2007
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Dominican Today - Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic [edited]
<http://www.dominicantoday.com/app/article.aspx?id=23451>

Three deaths and more than 1000 officially registered cases of dengue
so far this year [2007] casts doubts on the Health Ministry's
prevention plan against the disease.
Meanwhile, the numbers point to a highly epidemic dengue situation --
because of climatologic changes -- that will require RD 50 million
[USD 1.55 million] more this year [2007] to monitor.
However, the Health Ministry's Primary Assistance vice-minister and
head of the Program against Dengue, Nelson Rodriguez, defends the
work and affirms that their plan began in January [2007]. He said
that for that reason, they decided to bolster the campaign for the
disease's prevention through the National Day against Dengue or D-day.
The mobilization, to take place on 17 Apr 2007, aims to eliminate
water deposits [breeding sites] of the mosquito that transmits the
dengue virus and to reduce the disease's mortality, which Rodriguez
considers to be very high.
The official said that D-day is officially constituted and is part of
the activities that stress the importance of social participation in
the fight against dengue. Rodriguez said epidemiology authorities,
provincial health directorates, city councils and neighbors
associations work to eliminate the breeding sites of the vector that
carries the dengue virus.
He added that among the measures to be adopted are the training of
all public and private health personnel and the creation of the
Dengue Handling Committee, which consists of grouping the dengue
patients in one same area of the health center to facilitate their monitoring.
--
